es a new essay by Butler herself, from which it takes its title. Organized around four key themes in Butler's scholarship - performativity, speech, precarity, and assembly - the volume offers an excellent introduction to the contemporary relevance of Butler's thinking, a multi-perspectival approach to key topics of contemporary critical theory, and a testimony to the vibrant interdisciplinary discourses characterizing much of today's humanities' research.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aFeminist theory. 0aHuman body (Philosophy). 4aContemporary Society. 4aGender Studies. 4aPhilosophy. 4aSocial and Political Sciences. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh  aPerformativity, precarity, speech, bodies, psychic life.1 aButler, Judith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCavarero, Adriana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEwara, Eyo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFischer-Lichte, Erika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHalsema, Annemie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHalsema, Annemie, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHui, Tingting, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKwastek, Katja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKwastek, Katja, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNancy, Jean-Luc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOever, Roel van den, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOever, Roel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPeetz, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoei, Noa, econtributor.4ctb4